items.title: Food stamps, Canada's apology and US elections
items.author: Reuters
items.content:
<article>Federal judges order SNAP (https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/us-judge-blocks-trump-administration-suspending-food-aid-benefits-2025-10-31/)  benefits to continue, but it's unclear if payments will go through starting November 1. High-stakes elections in New Jersey and Virginia (https://www.reuters.com/world/us/can-democrats-find-their-footing-tight-new-jersey-governors-race-tests-trumps-2025-10-30/)  offer early signals for the 2026 midterms. Canada's Prime Minister Mark Carney apologizes to Trump (https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/canadas-carney-says-he-apologised-trump-over-reagan-ad-2025-11-01/)  over an anti-tariff ad. Plus, layoffs hit major companies (https://www.reuters.com/business/world-at-work/global-firms-slash-jobs-amid-weak-sentiment-ai-push-2025-10-29/) , some driven by AI.

items.title: China launches Shenzhou-21 mission to space station
items.author: Reuters
items.content:
<article>China launches Shenzhou-21 mission to space station
 
China's Shenzhou-21 space rocket and its crew, including the youngest member of its astronaut corps, blasted off atop a Long March-2F rocket from the Jiuquan Satellite Launch Centre in northwest China, Chinese state media reported.
 
It's the seventh mission to the permanently inhabited Chinese space station since it was completed in 2022.
 
We are deleting a post containing an incorrect video.
 
#space #china #astronaut #shenzhou #science</article>
